68
00:06:24,880 --> 00:06:26,880
Mousetraps.

69
00:06:32,400 --> 00:06:35,800
(Operatically) # Mousetraps #

70
00:06:38,800 --> 00:06:40,840
Say, why don't we try in here?

71
00:06:40,880 --> 00:06:43,160
Well, that's a very good thought.

72
00:07:13,480 --> 00:07:15,280
Psst.

73
00:07:31,640 --> 00:07:35,720
Why, good morning, madam.
Could we interest you in a mousetrap?

74
00:07:35,760 --> 00:07:38,880
- What kind?
- Any. We have the latest inventions.

75
00:07:38,920 --> 00:07:41,280
- Yes, we have...
- l'll handle this.

76
00:07:41,320 --> 00:07:43,880
- You will handle what?
- Good morning!

77
00:07:43,920 --> 00:07:47,680
- We'll show you our latest mousetraps.
- We don't want any.

78
00:07:47,720 --> 00:07:51,440
- Oh, let's take a look at one.
- We don't want to look at any.

79
00:07:51,480 --> 00:07:54,000
lf l want to look at a mousetrap, l will.

80
00:07:54,040 --> 00:07:55,920
l said no.

81
00:07:55,960 --> 00:07:57,680
l said yes.

82
00:07:58,560 --> 00:08:00,400
l said no.

83
00:08:13,440 --> 00:08:15,560
Don't you dare hit my husband.

84
00:08:17,600 --> 00:08:19,600
That goes for you, too.

85
00:08:19,640 --> 00:08:21,800
Oh, mama, that was nice of you.

86
00:08:21,840 --> 00:08:25,600
Now, if you want to look at a mousetrap,
look at one.

87
00:08:25,640 --> 00:08:31,480
Oh, papa! Mama changed her mind.
We don't wanna look at no mousetraps.

88
00:08:45,640 --> 00:08:47,760
Well, this is your idea.

89
00:08:47,800 --> 00:08:52,640
Coming all the way from America
to Switzerland to sell mousetraps.

90
00:08:52,680 --> 00:08:54,880
Whatever gave you that idea?

91
00:08:54,920 --> 00:08:57,320
l thought there'd be more mice here.

92
00:08:57,360 --> 00:09:01,600
And why should there be more mice here
than any place in the world?

93
00:09:01,640 --> 00:09:03,920
Don't they make more cheese here?

94
00:09:05,280 --> 00:09:09,840
Do you realise we've been here two weeks
and haven't sold one mousetrap

95
00:09:09,880 --> 00:09:12,240
- and we're flat broke?
- We're what?

96
00:09:12,280 --> 00:09:14,000
We're flat broke.

97
00:09:14,040 --> 00:09:16,640
Does that mean we haven't any money?

98
00:09:20,800 --> 00:09:23,800
- You know what the trouble is, don't you?
- No. What?

99
00:09:23,840 --> 00:09:26,320
We're not going to the right places.

100
00:09:26,360 --> 00:09:28,240
What do you mean?

101
00:09:28,280 --> 00:09:31,840
Suppose you were a mouse
and you wanted something to eat,

102
00:09:31,880 --> 00:09:33,760
where would you go?

103
00:09:33,800 --> 00:09:36,440
l'd go where there was cheese, of course.

104
00:09:36,480 --> 00:09:39,800
That's the idea.
Where there's cheese, there's mice.

105
00:09:39,840 --> 00:09:41,920
l still don't know what you mean.

106
00:09:41,960 --> 00:09:45,600
Why don't we go to
the cheese factories to sell them?

107
00:09:45,640 --> 00:09:47,920
Let me give that a little thought.

108
00:10:04,960 --> 00:10:09,680
You take the two small ones in and
come back and help me with the big one.

109
00:10:22,160 --> 00:10:26,240
Don't go away, we've got something
to show you. Stay here.

110
00:10:31,360 --> 00:10:33,360
All right.

111
00:11:05,080 --> 00:11:07,400
Look! Look what you do to my cheese!

112
00:11:07,440 --> 00:11:11,560
What are you trying to do?
Wreck my place of business?

113
00:11:11,600 --> 00:11:14,240
(Shouting incoherently)

114
00:11:17,440 --> 00:11:19,800
Just a moment, just a moment.

115
00:11:19,840 --> 00:11:23,280
Pardon this odd intrusion,
we really meant no harm.

116
00:11:23,320 --> 00:11:26,560
Don't get yourself a-flutter,
there's no need for alarm.

117
00:11:26,600 --> 00:11:29,920
We're selling something that you need
so won't you listen, please.

118
00:11:29,960 --> 00:11:33,600
We'll rid your place of all the mice
and we'll also save your cheese.

119
00:11:33,640 --> 00:11:35,640
- Won't we?
- Save my cheese?

120
00:11:35,680 --> 00:11:38,120
- Yes, sir.
- (Shopkeeper) Cosi.

121
00:11:38,160 --> 00:11:40,160
Fix me a hole.

122
00:11:40,200 --> 00:11:42,960
You put this trap in a conspicuous place.

123
00:11:48,640 --> 00:11:51,200
What you are making holes in my floor for?

124
00:11:51,240 --> 00:11:54,080
The mouse has to have someplace to get in.

125
00:11:54,120 --> 00:11:57,120
Maybe so. What's that cork for?

126
00:11:57,160 --> 00:11:59,400
That's so the mouse can't get out.

127
00:12:03,280 --> 00:12:06,280
What you are making
another hole in my floor for?

128
00:12:06,320 --> 00:12:10,440
That's because a mouse
never comes out of the same hole twice.

129
00:12:10,480 --> 00:12:12,480
Oh, is that so?

130
00:12:15,080 --> 00:12:17,080
Emile, come here.

131
00:12:18,680 --> 00:12:21,040
Shh, shh. Excuse, please.

132
00:12:25,040 --> 00:12:28,400
Why don't we make a lot of holes?
lt'll save time.

133
00:12:28,440 --> 00:12:31,040
That's a good idea. l'll help you.

134
00:12:31,080 --> 00:12:34,720
What are those men doing to our floor?

135
00:12:34,760 --> 00:12:37,360
They are trying to sell me mousetraps.

136
00:12:37,400 --> 00:12:40,400
Don't you waste
any good money on mousetraps.

137
00:12:40,440 --> 00:12:42,160
Who's wasting good money?

138
00:12:42,200 --> 00:12:45,640
Here's where l get rid of
those no-good Bovanian francs.

139
00:12:45,680 --> 00:12:47,720
Ja! l go get it for you.

140
00:12:47,760 --> 00:12:49,200
Hurry up.

141
00:12:57,920 --> 00:13:00,480
(Hissing)

142
00:13:05,760 --> 00:13:08,120
See what it is.

143
00:13:53,960 --> 00:13:59,240
Should we go downstairs and get some fire
and put the water out... l mean...

144
00:13:59,280 --> 00:14:03,800
The fire is out. For once in your life
you've acted with impunity.

145
00:14:07,760 --> 00:14:10,720
- Now l've an idea.
- (Both) You've an idea?

146
00:14:10,760 --> 00:14:14,160
l'll buy your whole business for 5,000 gule.

147
00:14:14,200 --> 00:14:17,200
Why, you being so generous,
we'll throw in our mule.

148
00:14:17,240 --> 00:14:19,800
You can't do that, don't be such a fool.

149
00:14:19,840 --> 00:14:22,480
- That's my idea.
- lt's a splendid idea.

150
00:14:22,520 --> 00:14:24,720
lt's just an idea of my own.

151
00:14:24,760 --> 00:14:26,600
# lt's just an idea

152
00:14:26,640 --> 00:14:28,800
# A splendid idea

153
00:14:28,840 --> 00:14:31,960
# lt's a just an idea of my own

154
00:14:32,000 --> 00:14:34,000
# (Very deep voice) Won't you

155
00:14:34,040 --> 00:14:38,360
# Roll dem

156
00:14:39,480 --> 00:14:43,280
# Bones #

157
00:14:50,920 --> 00:14:53,240
- How about some dessert?
- Uh-uh.

158
00:14:53,280 --> 00:14:54,960
- Waiter.
- Yes, sir?

159
00:14:55,000 --> 00:14:58,480
Bring me a large slice of apple pie
and a demitasse.

160
00:14:58,520 --> 00:15:00,240
Yes, sir. And you, sir?

161
00:15:00,280 --> 00:15:03,280
- l'll have... What?
- What will you have, sir?

162
00:15:03,320 --> 00:15:05,920
- l'll try some of that demitasse.
- Yes, sir.

163
00:15:05,960 --> 00:15:09,000
- And bring me a cup of coffee, too.
- Yes, sir.

164
00:15:12,400 --> 00:15:15,400
l hope everything is of your satisfaction.

165
00:15:15,440 --> 00:15:18,280
- l'm too full for words.
- Splendid.

166
00:15:18,320 --> 00:15:22,960
Chi assaggia il nostro cibo, ritorna,
as they say in Swiss.

167
00:15:25,280 --> 00:15:27,880
Sorry, sir, there is no apple pie.

168
00:15:27,920 --> 00:15:29,920
- No apple pie?
- No, sir.

169
00:15:29,960 --> 00:15:32,200
Just what kind of a hotel is this?

170
00:15:32,240 --> 00:15:35,880
l am sorry. Maybe we have
some other kind you would like?

171
00:15:35,920 --> 00:15:39,680
No, sir. l have my mouth
all set for apple pie.

172
00:15:39,720 --> 00:15:42,320
- Send the chef to me at once.
- Yes, sir.

173
00:15:42,360 --> 00:15:46,480
- l will go to the bottom of this.
- See that you do.

174
00:15:46,520 --> 00:15:49,080
What is the meaning? Why no apple pie?

175
00:15:49,120 --> 00:15:51,280
Yes, what is the meaning?

176
00:15:51,320 --> 00:15:54,760
- What do you say?
- Don't stand there like a jackass!

177
00:15:54,800 --> 00:15:56,600
Why isn't there apple pie?

178
00:15:56,640 --> 00:15:59,840
Why don't you tell him?
He's got his face upset for it.

179
00:15:59,880 --> 00:16:01,480
Say something!

180
00:16:01,520 --> 00:16:03,400
Let me tell you something.

181
00:16:03,440 --> 00:16:08,000
l've had better chefs than you
discharged for not having apple pie.

182
00:16:08,040 --> 00:16:09,920
Absolutely.

183
00:16:09,960 --> 00:16:14,600
He shall be released
if he cannot tell why no apple pie.

184
00:16:14,640 --> 00:16:17,240
Make apple pie. Make lots of apple pie!

185
00:16:17,280 --> 00:16:19,880
Yes! Make a hundred apple pies.

186
00:16:19,920 --> 00:16:21,880
And make me an apple dumpling.

187
00:16:21,920 --> 00:16:23,720
You numbskull.

188
00:16:23,760 --> 00:16:25,920
Yeah, and that goes for him, too.

189
00:16:26,880 --> 00:16:29,640
l am sorry to cause you this inconvenient.

190
00:16:29,680 --> 00:16:32,840
l promise it never will happen again.

191
00:16:32,880 --> 00:16:35,680
Aw, just skip it. Bring me the bill.

192
00:16:35,720 --> 00:16:37,720
Waiter, the bill.

193
00:16:39,400 --> 00:16:43,560
Take it out of that and
bring me the change in American currency -

194
00:16:43,600 --> 00:16:45,520
large denominations.

195
00:16:50,600 --> 00:16:53,080
That is some funny joke.

196
00:16:53,120 --> 00:16:57,320
You Americans give always to me
a sense of humour.

197
00:17:02,040 --> 00:17:08,120
Now stop the monkey business and give me
some real money that l can pay the bill.

198
00:17:08,160 --> 00:17:11,920
What do you mean?
You've got 5,000 francs in that bill.

199
00:17:11,960 --> 00:17:14,160
They are no good in this country.

200
00:17:15,160 --> 00:17:18,720
- Well, where are they good?
- ln Bovania.

201
00:17:18,760 --> 00:17:21,080
Maybe we'd better go to Bovania.

202
00:17:21,120 --> 00:17:22,920
Where is Bovania?

203
00:17:22,960 --> 00:17:25,280
There is no such place.

204
00:17:27,640 --> 00:17:29,880
What are we going to do about it?

205
00:17:29,920 --> 00:17:33,760
What are you going to do?
You are going to pay the bill.

206
00:17:33,800 --> 00:17:36,320
That's all the money we've got.

207
00:17:36,360 --> 00:17:39,960
Questa é una truffa ben regolata!

208
00:17:40,000 --> 00:17:42,880
Don't drink that coffee!

209
00:17:42,920 --> 00:17:45,600
You come with me, come on. Come on.

210
00:17:45,640 --> 00:17:47,440
Come on.

211
00:17:49,320 --> 00:17:51,320
Put that down!

212
00:17:55,960 --> 00:17:57,960
What do you think has happened?

213
00:17:58,000 --> 00:18:02,200
After so much fuss about the apple pie
they cannot pay the bill

214
00:18:02,240 --> 00:18:04,120
so l put them to work.

215
00:18:04,160 --> 00:18:06,120
You will tell them what to do.

216
00:18:06,160 --> 00:18:08,520
And if they break any dishes -

217
00:18:08,560 --> 00:18:12,520
for every dish they break, work another day.

218
00:18:12,560 --> 00:18:14,760
Both of you! Go ahead.

219
00:18:19,960 --> 00:18:24,440
So, you bragged about
discharging better chefs than me?

220
00:18:24,480 --> 00:18:26,280
Didn't you?

221
00:18:27,320 --> 00:18:30,040
There are no better chefs than me.

222
00:18:30,080 --> 00:18:31,880
Are there?!

223
00:18:32,680 --> 00:18:34,680
Are there?

224
00:18:38,520 --> 00:18:40,840
You remember what the boss said.

225
00:18:40,880 --> 00:18:45,080
For every dish you break,
you'll work an extra day.

226
00:18:48,920 --> 00:18:50,720
Hold it.

227
00:18:58,080 --> 00:19:00,080
Catch!

228
00:19:03,600 --> 00:19:05,600
Come on.

229
00:19:15,280 --> 00:19:17,280
One day, two days.

230
00:19:18,240 --> 00:19:20,960
By the time you leave this place

231
00:19:21,000 --> 00:19:25,560
the grey hairs of your beards
will be trailing on this kitchen floor.

232
00:19:32,200 --> 00:19:34,800
(Chirping)

233
00:19:34,840 --> 00:19:37,400
Edward! Edward! Where in the name...

234
00:19:37,440 --> 00:19:39,120
Coming, sir.

235
00:19:39,160 --> 00:19:42,240
Edward, what's making
that noise in my head?

236
00:19:42,280 --> 00:19:44,120
l'm sure l don't know, sir.

237
00:19:44,160 --> 00:19:46,360
Can't you hear it? Listen.

238
00:19:48,000 --> 00:19:50,320
(Chirping)

239
00:19:55,560 --> 00:19:59,640
Bless your heart, sir.
That's not in your head, that's a cricket.

240
00:19:59,680 --> 00:20:01,880
- A cricket?
- Yes, sir.

241
00:20:03,000 --> 00:20:07,280
- The cricket song.
- That's not bad, sir. Not bad at all.

242
00:20:13,120 --> 00:20:15,120
# Hear the cricket

243
00:20:15,160 --> 00:20:19,800
# Singing merrily all day long

244
00:20:19,840 --> 00:20:23,280
# Click, click, click hear the cricket

245
00:20:23,320 --> 00:20:28,160
# Yea, it is verily quite a song

246
00:20:28,200 --> 00:20:31,600
# He seems to know what is due from him

247
00:20:31,640 --> 00:20:33,560
# Each tune is new from him

248
00:20:33,600 --> 00:20:35,840
# Let's take a cue from him

249
00:20:35,880 --> 00:20:38,480
# With a click, click, click

250
00:20:38,520 --> 00:20:40,200
# Hear the cricket

